Populism refers to a range of political stances that emphasize the idea of "the people" against "the elite," often simplifying complex issues and promoting a charismatic leader as the solution.
According to the ideational approach, populism emphasizes the importance of the collective will of the people over traditional political elites.
The term populism came into use in the late 19th century to describe a political movement that champions the common people against the elites.
In 1967 a Conference on Populism led to heated debates among scholars and politicians about the roots and implications of the populist movement.
