Penal populism is a process whereby the fear of crime drives harsher criminal justice policies and practices, often resulting in increased incarceration rates.
Penal populism generally reflects the disenchantment felt by a society seeking harsher punishments for criminals to restore a sense of justice and security.
The term changed to 'penal populism' when politicians began using tough-on-crime rhetoric to gain popularity among voters, regardless of its impact on the criminal justice system.
Salas says that in France, penal populism has contributed to the rise of harsher criminal justice policies.
Market populism, coined by Thomas Frank, is a term used to describe the exploitation of populist sentiments for corporate gain.
